14. The securitisation should be such that the underlying credit claims or receivables:
a) are enforceable against the obligor and their enforceability is included in the representations and warranties of the originator;
b) are beyond the reach of the seller, its creditors or liquidators and are not subject to material recharacterisation or clawback risks;
c) are not effected through credit default swaps, derivatives or guarantees, but by a transfer of the credit claims or the receivables to the securitisation;
d) demonstrate effective recourse to the ultimate obligation for the underlying credit claims or receivables and are not a securitisation of other securitisations; and
e) for regulatory capital purposes, an independent third-party legal opinion must support the claim that the transfer of assets under the applicable laws comply with the above sub-clauses.

